  "prompt": "How likely will LASIK vision deteriorate with age if one had stable prescription before the operation?",
  "response": "LASIK (Laser-Assisted In Situ Keratomileusis) is a popular surgical procedure designed to correct refractive vision problems such as myopia (nearsightedness), hyperopia (farsightedness), and astigmatism. Generally, many people enjoy stable vision after LASIK for years, especially if they had a stable prescription before the operation.\n\nHowever, while LASIK can significantly reduce dependence on glasses or contact lenses, it does not prevent age-related vision changes. Common conditions that may develop with age include:\n\n1. **Presbyopia**: Typically occurring after the age of 40, presbyopia is a natural loss of the eye\u2019s ability to focus on close objects. This affects nearly everyone regardless of whether they have had LASIK.\n\n2. **Cataracts**: The risk of cataracts increases with age. Cataracts can cause clouding of the lens in the eye, potentially impacting vision even after LASIK.\n\n3. **Other age-related conditions**: Retina problems, glaucoma, and macular degeneration can also affect eyesight as people age.\n\nWhile it's difficult to predict how an individual\u2019s vision will change with age post-LASIK, a person with a stable prescription prior to surgery may have a lower risk of significant refractive changes immediately after the procedure. However, they may still experience the typical age-related vision changes that occur over time.\n\nTo maintain optimal eye health and vision, regular eye examinations are recommended, especially as one ages. If you have concerns about your vision after LASIK or any changes you experience over time, it\u2019s best to consult with an eye care professional.",
